*Assessment*

While verifying EUCA-10271, the cloudformation template contained the following for the AWS::EC2::SubnetNetworkAclAssociation resource:
{code}
        "NetworkAcl2DefaultACL2AssociationSet20": {
            "Properties": {
                "NetworkAclId": {
                    "Ref": "NetworkAcl2DefaultACL"
                },
                "Tags": [ {"Key" : "Application", "Value" : { "Ref" : "AWS::StackId"}} ],
                "SubnetId": {
                    "Ref": "Subnet2subnet0"
                }
            },
            "Type": "AWS::EC2::SubnetNetworkAclAssociation"
        },
{code}
Per [AWS Cloudformation documentation regarding AWS::EC2::SubnetNetworkAclAssociation|http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-resource-ec2-subnet-network-acl-assoc.html], Tags are not part of "Properties":
{code}
"Type" : "AWS::EC2::SubnetNetworkAclAssociation",
"Properties" : {
   "SubnetId" : { String }
   "NetworkAclId" : { String }
}
{code}
Since this is the case, when the stack fails to deploy on Eucalyptus (just as on AWS), there should be the following error in the stack events:
{code}
STACKEVENTS	NetworkAcl2DefaultACL2AssociationSet20-CREATE_FAILED-1421291983962	NetworkAcl2DefaultACL2AssociationSet20	None		CREATE_FAILED	Encountered unsupported property Tags	AWS::EC2::SubnetNetworkAclAssociation	arn:aws:cloudformation:us-east-1:048212016277:stack/UbuntuVividStack/3dbca280-9c65-11e4-8ceb-50fa1dbb2c64	UbuntuVividStack	2015-01-15T03:19:43.962Z
{code}
Currently, Eucalyptus Cloudformation shows the following error in the stack events:
{code}

fields.summary: Cloudformation:  AWS::EC2::SubnetNetworkAclAssociation Property Error Not Returned When Stack Fails

comments.body: [~hspencer]  I'm not sure I understand what the bug is here.  You say when "Tags" is embedded within the "Properties" fields, AWS returns an error, and this may be true.  (I will have to verify that), but the example output you give for stack failure on Eucalyptus fails on a different element entirely: SecurityGroup2DefaultSG2Ingress20.  I suspect there may be two errors here.  Is there something else other than Eucalyptus not failing if an unsupported property exists?  Please elaborate.
The failure of this stack on eucalytpus is due to EUCA-10352.

[~ethomas],

Yes, there are two issues here.  Apologies for not making that clear.  The issues are as follows:
\\
\\
* When "Tags" is embedded within a "Properties" field for a resource that doesn't support it (e.g. [AWS::EC2::SubnetNetworkAclAssociation|http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-resource-ec2-subnet-network-acl-assoc.html])
* Looks like something causes Eucalyptus to fail in a different place entirely than compared to AWS (fail at _SecurityGroup2DefaultSG2Ingress20_ versus _NetworkAcl2DefaultACL2AssociationSet20_).  Looking at the workflow, it looks like on AWS, the following resource flow is performed regarding "CREATE_COMPLETE" state on VPC:
\\
\\
** AWS::EC2::InternetGateway -> AWS::EC2::VPC -> AWS::EC2::VPCGatewayAttachment -> *AWS::EC2::SecurityGroup* -> *AWS::EC2::Subnet* -> *AWS::EC2::RouteTable* -> *AWS::EC2::NetworkAcl* -> *AWS::EC2::SubnetNetworkAclAssociation (Failed)*
\\
\\
Versus Eucalyptus:
** AWS::EC2::InternetGateway -> AWS::EC2::VPC -> AWS::EC2::VPCGatewayAttachment -> *AWS::EC2::NetworkAcl* -> *AWS::EC2::RouteTable* -> *AWS::EC2::Subnet* -> *AWS::EC2::SecurityGroup* -> *AWS::EC2::Route* -> *AWS::EC2::SubnetRouteTableAssociation* -> *AWS::EC2::SubnetNetworkAclAssociation* -> *AWS::EC2::SecurityGroupIngress (Fail)*

I am not sure if this matters or not , but thats what I see different between the AWS stack events and the Eucalyptus stack events when using the same cloudformation template.

Does that help?  If you think the second observation is an issue, I can open a separate ticket on it.  Thanks for the ping back on this.

[~ethomas], the bug summary seems ok to me, we would need a doc ticket for the new property. The fix looks good to me.

It looks like the default for the new property is false, in which case the issue would not be fixed unless running with a non-default configuration. I think if we are implementing this functionality we should enable it on new installs (probably not for upgrades?)

[~sjones] Is there a way to make the property 'false' for upgrade and 'true' for new installs?  Also, this should allow existing stacks to upgrade, so maybe we don't need to make it false for upgrade?
[~ethomas], you could create the property with the desired value on upgrade. I'm not sure whether it is better to enable strict checking on upgrade or not.
